The New Issue: File Access Locking & Resource Latency
Now that the app is successfully pointing to the hostdaemon.log, we have encountered a common "Windows-ism": Concurrent Access Conflicts.

The Problem:
Because the hostdaemon on the Windows Server is frequently writing to the log file, the Streamlit app occasionally hits a PermissionError (Error 13). Windows is locking the file for writing, which prevents our Python regex engine from opening it for reading. Furthermore, as the log grows in size, performing a full regex sweep on every UI interaction is causing Streamlit to lag.

Solutions in Development
To keep the search utility responsive and "crash-proof," I am implementing the following logic:

1. Non-Blocking Read (The "Shadow Copy" Method)
Instead of opening the active log directly, the utility will now utilize a temporary buffer or the shutil.copy2 method. This allows us to read a "snapshot" of the log without triggering a file-lock conflict with the host daemon.
